column1: Before 1 January 2023, how many major automakers will debut a passenger vehicle powered by a solid-state battery?
column6: ['Business', 'Technology', 'Environment']

The years 2022 and 2023 appear to be the advent of solid-state cars. Toyota seem to be ahead of the pack possibly due its policy of developing a solid-state battery in-house whereas all the other major car manufacturers having entered joint ventures with battery producers. Toyota’s advantage being that it is control of its own engineering processes and budgetary concerns. The question does specify the debut of a model rather than an on-road offer. Car Manufacturers seemingly in place to debut cars are: Toyota Ford BMW NIO VW(?)

It would appear from the various trade reports that a viable solid-state battery powered car will be available between 2023 and 2025. General Motors in a development with SES (Singapore) is aiming to produce such a battery in 2023. Volkswagen in conjunction with QuantumScape of California suggest 2025. Tesla has issued no plans. A solid-state battery dispenses with a liquid or gel but allows the lithium to pass through. This allows for a smaller, lighter unit with more energy. Toyota is designing its battery in-house to be on the market in the early 2020’s. The question, one assumes to a vehicle commercially available rather than a concept type. The likelihood of such of a vehicle appearing prior to January 1st 2023 seems presumptuous.
If the marketing communications director can spell "solid state" it will be debuted. Dogs & Cats will debut that are solid state.
There are going to be major swings in this direction. Everyone will get on board, particularly because the vehicle does not need to be solely powered by battery, so hybrids will count

New regulations in the EU and China and increased attention from US manufacturer Ford and its Lightning Pickup truck will continue to add motivation for alternative battery technology to the horizon. If the cost and reliance of SSB continues to improve manufacturers may choose SSB over Lithium Ion.

Toyota, GM, Ford, BMW, VW, maybe Benz, once the leaders do it, everyman and his dog will have one. Debut means show one at a major trade show, nothing more, and have glossy press releases about the "future" of electric cars is now.

Just recently BMW announced that they will publish a demonstrator vehicle before 2025. It's unlikely that it will be in the course of 2022, though. Of course, this is only one manufacturer and it could be that they are not the most advanced, but even if others are quicker in development of the technology, it takes a couple of years (at least one) to then also integrate a new battery technology in a concept car.
it's unlikely that a solid state battery EV will be publicly available by that date. it is possible one may be showcase in exhibition.
Every major car company will have an electric division, if they don't already have one. Also, less moving parts (in the vehicle) means that production can be quicker.

The key here is a semantic one, namely the definition of “debut”. My answer assumes that “debut” means make available for sale to the general public. The technology is not mature enough to support manufacture in the given time frame, even on the smallest scale.
VW, Toyota, GM, and there will others who need to make a show.

China EV battery race: Tesla’s rivals join NIO in efforts to achieve 1,000km driving range on single charge target • NIO was the first to put the 1,000km range on its ET7 sedan specification, to be fitted with a 150kWh solid-state battery when it goes into production in 2022 • Chinese partners of General Motors, Toyota and Honda have also announced efforts to develop cutting-edge batteries that can go the distance China’s electric car assemblers and battery producers are setting a new goalpost in their battle for supremacy in the world’s largest vehicle market: a driving range of up to 1,000 kilometers (621 miles) on a single charge.

The preponderance of guesses in this crowd that overestimate the likelihood that a solid-state vehicle will hit the road in the next two years leads me to believe that very few in this group follow battery tech or the EV space very closely. Solid state battery tech isn't likely to achieve commercial viability at any level in the vehicle space certainly in the first half of this decade but probably not even in the second half. I allow for a fat tail chance that QS can put their batteries in some vehicle in the next two years but think that it is both very unlikely and almost certainly in a prototype model or an extremely small number of vehicles for economic and manufacturing reasons.
They are hard to build at scale and durability (charge cycles) could be an issues till 2025 timeframes.

Question still to vague- full powered like a QS; and solid state for part of solution/marketing seems likely - 2 years, yet Toy. Tesla are offering improved, but not yet solid state.... improved for sure - "just as good as" Rapid high power is all consumers care about - vs. valan. or lit solid state/qs etc. still uncertain -

https://cleantechnica.com/2020/12/11/solid-state-batteries-theyre-everywhere-theyre-everywhere/ https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Most-read-in-2020/Toyota-s-game-changing-solid-state-battery-en-route-for-2021-debut
Toyota and Tesla. Perhaps Mercedes-Benz. GM?
They may ‘debut’ as in build 5 units for demo etc. But not in the >5k per year volume

Looks like several major automakers are looking to begin production on vehicles with solid-state batteries in 2024 and 2025. The technology looks like it is reaching the final stages of development and is viable for commercial applications. Companies will likely be debuting prototype vehicles in order to generate publicity and possibly pre-orders over the next two years. Two years is a long time especially for technology so at this point it probably better to expect several automakers to make these announcements. Therefore, my forecast is slanted towards a higher number of automakers debuting these vehicles.

I hate betting against a fast learning curve. Lithium ion is on one right now. I'm betting that the various car makers back off of these designs. They might "debut" something, but I don't think any make it into mass production.
The world is a weird place if this question resolves at <3-4
Many companies are working on solid state battery solutions. As of Dec 2020 Toyota says they'll have a working prototype in 2021: https://www.motortrend.com/news/toyota-solid-state-battery-ev-2021/

Toyota says 2021, Tesla can’t be far behind (even if they can’t deliver it)... VW wants a piece of the sustainable action. Count in BMW, Daimler and Ford. Solid State. So hot right now. It’s a shame that for the purposes of this question we’re using a list from 2017, otherwise we could add Nio to the list. That said, it’s old school business strat that these folks want to claim first to market (and rub Elon’s nose in it.) This may end up like a “when it rains, it pours” situation.

By Dec 2022 every man and his dog will have debuted a solid state battery, and most automakers, too. If you don't offer an EV you're not in the game, if you don't offer a solid state battery you'll loose the game. This will be painful for marginal players.

https://cnevpost.com/2021/01/08/nio-to-launch-150-kwh-solid-state-battery-pack/ I am increasing the probability of 3 or 4, reducing the probability of 0 based on this press release. It is only a small(-ish) company, not listed on the 50 car manufacturers, but it they can do it then so can others. I stand by my reasoning that solid-state isn't that exciting for a debut and we are a way off having a workable vehicle.

Solid state cells offer a good safety solution to Li-ion, but there are problems surrounding the energy density. Recent developments out of Quantumscape (massively funded by VW) show the promise, but they have not translated that into mass production yet. That step must be met before any trials on cars with solid state cells. The trials must precede any sales. But these debuts do not require such stringent conditions. The question leaves open what must be debuted. Does the car need to move? Would it need to actually have the cells and a usable cockpit and not be some empty shell? I presume yes. Furthermore, the vast majority of solid state cells are pouch cells whereas most of the EVs are using the cylindrical 18650s. The size differences will mean that the structural changes to a vehicle will not be trivial. A whole new chassis may be required with the passengers being moved up ~5 cm. This shouldn't be too difficult for a show vehicle. For all the excitement around solid state, to debut a car like this a company will most likely already be manufacturing (or partnering on that) already. That limits the number of companies down to maybe 5/6. I'm lacking knowledge of just how adventurous a manufacturer would be on a debut. Also, how interesting would this be at a car show? To what extent is an EV just an EV to the viewers?

Not sure where the sweet spot is on this. But all majors will have to move in this direction to stay in business and vaporware debuts are one way to stay in the news while you scramble looking for a supplier.

Apple targets car production by 2024 and eyes 'next level' battery technology PUBLISHED MON, DEC 21 2020 3:48 PM EST UPDATED MON, DEC 21 2020 4:14 PM EST SHARE KEY POINTS Apple is moving forward with self-driving car technology and is targeting 2024 to produce a passenger vehicle that could include its own breakthrough battery technology, people familiar with the matter told Reuters. The iPhone maker's automotive efforts, known as Project Titan, have proceeded unevenly since 2014 when it first started to design its own vehicle from scratch. At one point, Apple drew back the effort to focus on software and reassessed its goals. Since then, Apple has progressed enough that it now aims to build a vehicle for consumers, two people familiar with the effort said
It will be hard to compete without an EV, and the place to be will be solid state. Hey we are looking 2 years out.

VW and Toyota world's largest automakers are already committed. Others will be scrambling to "me too" their debuts so as to not be left out of the conversation. Products not likely until 2025. Marginal players will be quickly sidelined as the cost to compete is very high.

I'll assume this will be at least VW and Toyota and probably 2 others like GM or BMW. Apparently, this will be a thing in 2025-2026, so debuts in 2022 are likely to prep the market, as long as they don't Osborne themselves by announcing too early and stalling other sales.

Here’s the game changer (or first step in process) everyone has been looking for. https://www.wired.com/story/quantumscape-solid-state-battery/ Still going to be a few years (2025?) before on road, but look for “debut” prior to this.
I really wish I had not answered this question. It's so openended.
Maybe that'll be one of the debuts:
Back to where we started, but it was worth asking...
Update: I had the misconception that debut means that the car is production ready.

A quick look at the references provided by @Hammer-Time indicates that there should be several debuts in the next two years, even if there is no product until 2025 at the earliest. In the meantime the only company to put money on is TSLA in this space - they are designing the machines to make their batteries while others are still hand crafting lab models wearing white coats.

Years away but a few are getting closer... https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a31409442/samsung-solid-state-battery-revealed/ https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a33435923/toyota-solid-state-battery-2025/ https://insideevs.com/news/444449/mercedes-benz-ecitaro-g-solid-state-battery/ https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1129497_vw-backed-solid-state-battery-firm-quantumscape-is-going-public By “debut”, I believe functional prototypes count.
This is such a long shot, I'll sit on the fence if it even happens.
Toyota is projecting 2025. I doubt if any OEMs are going to be quick to produce anything. They tend to be behind the 8-ball on most projects.
It's not clear what solid state means, at least to me. Does the TSLA battery day dry cathode count as a solid state battery?
Waiting on whether this counts as a "debut" for a "passenger vehicle" ... https://www.autoblog.com/2020/09/15/mercedes-benz-solid-state-battery-tech-bus/
Worth considering: https://insideevs.com/news/443450/ex-tesla-solid-state-batteries-false-hope/amp/
Correcting for my tendency to be over-optimistic on these issues.

I'm not sure I can do much better than this... whether we have 0-2 probably has the chances of an unfair coin toss. I share the crowd's pain. Any of these 50 automakers could debut solid state aspirations the enjoy the PR bump.
We will see what Battery Day brings to the table.

We have a 2-1/2 years for something to debut or NOT. Manufacturers are desperate to showcase something that they can sell, not Osborne themselves by showcasing non-existant technology. Manufacturers will be debuting conventional batteries because that is what they can deliver in the next few years, not magic. Most manufacturers are desperate to find a business model for EV's that works for them and their dealers. Solid state doesn't help that.

The technology itself looks like its still about 3-7 years away from being ready to be used in a vehicle. Most vehicle debuts happen about 1-2 years in advance based on some quick research. There is a chance that future concept cars get announced (as they inevitably do around new technologies for marketing buzz), and based on how this question is worded, its hard to know if that would count or not
If the technology arrives it is likely to be become quickly distributed, but there is a large chance that it does not take off in the timeframe. My probability density therefore creates a u shape.

When we say "debut," I guess it just means someone on stage saying "look at our new car..." (I'm exaggerating.) But based on the criteria, not much more is needed. Announced in NOV 2019, Cybertruck is due out 2021. Lyriq was announced AUG 2020 and due 2022. So we're talking a two year lag on announcement and release. Its tough to say. "No" is a compelling bucket, but at least 1 feels possible.

Interesting if imprecise question. @keith-huggins has some good links posted below. Here's another one: https://www.msn.com/en-us/autos/news/new-battery-tech-will-pull-electric-vehicles-even-with-petrol-fueled-cars/ar-BB182z3F.

A debut is not even a prototype, just a mock up model to gather feedback. Put a solid state battery to light the light in the glove box and you've met the requirements for this question. I am sorry to be so negative but the bar to clear for this question is so low as to be meaningless. It doesn't have to go to production and doesn't have to power the car. What is the point?

The question here could be construed as somewhat ambiguous, in that does the debut of a vehicle powered by a solid-state battery mean a working roadworthy model? Is a prototype considered as a model to be debut? A lithium-ion battery is an evolution of the chemical or liquid gel and is used on the EV models debut so far. The solid-state used a solid electrolyte and are a few years away for use in commercial vehicles. Toyota may have a prototype in 2020, but one assumes this is not considered a passenger vehicle ready for use. Samsung have made a breakthrough but state it is years away from commercial use.

I wish I had not answered this question. Debut is a nebulous term, counting vehicles that are not solely powered by a solid state battery allows any manufacturer to showcase a car with any non-production ready solid state battery and meet the weak bar set by this question. The vehicle never has to be built, just debuted in an announcement to count. There is no bar to entry for any manufacturerer to just debut. Flying car debuts would have been a more rigorous question.

Mercedes-Benz: John B. Goodenough co-invented the Lithium-Ion battery toghether with M. Stanley Whittingham, Rachid Yazami and Koichi Mizushima . [1] He also invented the glass battery. [3] Sources in March 2020 claim that Hydro-Quebec targets the year 2022 where solid state batteries will be "production ready". [5] In April 2020 the joint venture projects that the solid state battery will be production ready in 2026. [4] --> To me the announcement made in March is deprecated. The new goal is 2026.
EV sector is hot, everyone wants to be the next Tesla.

Does the technology exist today, no. Will it exist in a year, maybe. Will it exist at scale such that a manufacturer would be able to guarantee 8 years of operation - that is the crux of this question. We have 2 years and 4 months to find out. I am not holding my breath for that long. If it's mentioned at Battery Day, I'll change my forecast.
Like many other problems, this seems to be a problem of incentives.
